          "title": "The catalog of materials — the whole creation consecrated",
          "body": "Verses 5-9 and 11-19 constitute an elaborate inventory: gold, silver, bronze, colored textiles, fine linen, goats' hair, animal skins, acacia wood, oil, spices, incense, precious stones, priestly garments. The list covers metals from the earth, fibers from animals and plants, aromatics from the ancient Near Eastern trade routes, and stones from Sinai itself. The sheer material density of the list resists any spiritualizing reading of the tabernacle. God intends a physical structure, made of real materials gathered by real people, inhabited by the genuinely present God. The physical extravagance of the tabernacle is not a concession to Israel's primitive sensibilities; it is a statement about the character of God who meets His people in tangible, sensory ways. The materials listed here will reappear in the construction narratives of chapters 36-39 in almost verbatim correspondence, sealing the connection between what God commanded and what Israel provided. Douglas Stuart (WBC) notes that the repeated inventory serves a canonical purpose: the reader is meant to feel the weight of the community's full compliance."
