          "title": "The restored community — apostasy reversed, covenant renewed in action",
          "body": "Read in its canonical location — after the golden calf (ch. 32), after Moses's intercession (ch. 33), after the covenant renewal (ch. 34) — Exodus 35 functions as the narrative proof of restored covenant relationship. Covenant renewal in Exodus is not merely declared; it is demonstrated. The same congregation that danced before the calf, that had Aaron melt their gold into an idol, now voluntarily strips off their gold again, but this time for the sanctuary of the living God. The chapter's theological argument is not stated; it is enacted. Restoration from apostasy does not look like a sentimental recommitment. It looks like this: a whole community showing up with what they have, giving what their hands have made, offering what the Spirit has gifted them to offer, within the Sabbath rhythms God has established. Howard Hendricks wrote that the Christian life is caught before it is taught — Exodus 35 shows an entire covenant community catching what covenant faithfulness actually looks like in material, bodily, communal practice."
